There are fundamentally two forms of exercise

1. For war, which is done by lower classes and focuses on endurance, sustainability, training to cover large distances on grain as fuel

2. For recreation, done by aristocracy, for fun and consisting of achieving diff physical feats

Good example of first is Spartans, good example of second is ancient Greek bodybuilding, as per @LindyFit. For the latter you need physical abundance, need to have lots of good quality foods, meats, dairy, etc. to sustain yourself. First just turns you into a war-machine (bad).

For the peasantry, work is done in sunlight, and rest is in shadow, under a tree at noon, coming back home after a day of tilling in the field.

For the upper class, it's opposite, leisure is placed in the sunlight. Big gardens, going to beach, tennis. Leisure in the sunlight.

When you have access to good cholesterol-rich nutrition, through sunlight it just turns into hormones. It feels good. If you don't eat right, sun is not so nice.

Also, with good nutrition, aristocrats always grew to be taller, better-developed, stronger. Peasants were weaker.
